hands_on_practices.problem:
A sample of 2-pentanone (C₅H₁₀O) is analyzed by Electron Ionization Mass Spectrometry (EI-MS). The fragmentation pattern shows two prominent peaks that result from the two possible $\alpha$-cleavage reactions of the molecular ion. The term $\alpha$-cleavage refers to the homolytic cleavage of a carbon-carbon bond adjacent (alpha) to the carbonyl group, where the positive charge is retained by the oxygen-containing fragment. For your calculations, use integer atomic masses: C = 12, H = 1, O = 16. Which of the following pairs represents the mass-to-charge (m/z) ratios of the two cationic fragments produced by these two distinct $\alpha$-cleavage pathways?

A. {m/z = 15, m/z = 43}
B. {m/z = 43, m/z = 58}
C. {m/z = 43, m/z = 71}
D. {m/z = 58, m/z = 71}
E. {m/z = 29, m/z = 57}
